                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d776">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.94/1316a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-15T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 15, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>461. In response to inquiries in regard to the Soviet-Japanese pact, I made the
                    following statement to the press on April 14: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The significance of the pact between the Soviet Union and Japan relating
                            to neutrality, as reported in the press today, could be overestimated.
                            The agreement would seem to be descriptive of a situation <pb
                                facs="0957" n="949" xml:id="pg_949"/> which has in effect existed
                            between the two countries for some time past. It therefore comes as no
                            surprise, although there has existed doubt whether the two Governments
                            would or would not agree to say it in writing. The policy of this
                            Government of course remains unchanged.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
